Aristotle discusses (Poet. 8) the proper length of a tragedy, but in rela- tion to the plot, laying down the rule that it must be of sufficient compass to make the catastrophe probable, and not so long as to overtax the memory and lose unity of view (τὸ εὐσύνοπτον). Horace is adopting, perhaps after Alex— andrine critics, a more mechanical measurement.
